We feel we are blessed with education, expertise and resources to launch and build organizations of all types and it is for these reasons that we wish to help launch and grow startups around the world.
For each new client we work with, we dedicate $100 to a Kiva microloan. These microloans help entrepreneurs across the globe start or run their businesses.
lender.occupational_info:
Q: What do Apple, Google, and San Diego’s VAVI Sport & Social Club have in common?
A: They all began in someone’s garage.
Founded in 2008 by serial entrepreneur, Tyler Jensen, The Startup Garage is a community of business partners, specialists, tools, and business planning services that together with your brilliant business concepts, help bring your entrepreneurial dreams to life.
When Tyler began his third entrepreneurial venture, San Diego’s VAVI Sport and Social Club, in his garage at the age of 22, he was forced to work tirelessly to find the right formula for his business success. It worked, and VAVI became the 30th and 32nd fastest growing private company in San Diego in 2006 and 2007. However, Tyler found himself burnt out from years of working around the clock building his businesses. He sold VAVI in 2008 and set out to create a new way of being an entrepreneur.
Tyler began creating systems to help entrepreneurs create successful businesses without burning out. Through his own business ventures, Tyler learned the importance of a customized business plan as a means for a successful business. He believes that when people thrive, their businesses do too, and through his business planning services and The Startup Garage community, entrepreneurs and their businesses now have a proven system to find success and fulfillment of their dreams through expert support.
The Startup Garage Community looks forward to helping you bring your entrepreneurial dreams to life!

lender.occupational_info:
I am currently a full time student in college, and I am almost ready to attend university. I am studying Computer Science to learn how to write software for computers, and build and operate websites and systems.
During the summer I built a website to give individuals better access to very short term online work "tasks." I evaluated the data I collected from users over a 4 month period and was amazed to find that 80% of the workers who participated were from India, Pakistan, Africa (in general), and other regions of similar economic status. During the existence of the website I was able to pay out nearly $10,000 to individuals. The realization that the short term work I provided ended up being outsourced to countries where the pay seemed much more competitive really excited me about the opportunities for offering work to individuals around the world. It is my hope, and my desire to continue this research and eventually create a website which combines what I've learned in a way that helps people find outsourced work.
